# GENERAL SAPIC+ INSTRUCTIONS

## `new`: process block vs role's `let` block

- `process:` block → value SHARED across roles/instances. Place above
  both roles. Used for: common keys, channel names.

      process:
      !( new k; ( !Client(k) | !Server(k) ) )

- Inside a role's `let` → value PRIVATE to that role only. Used for:
  long-term keys.

      let Client() = new ~ltkA; let pkA = pk(~ltkA) in ...

## Channels

A channel is just the first argument to `in(...)`/`out(...)` — declare
it with `new` in `process:` (same SHARED rule as above) so all roles
reference the same name:

    let Client = new cr; out(c, <'client_hello', cr>)
    let Server = in(c, <'client_hello', cr>)

    process:
        new c;                    // shared channel
        ( !Client | !Server )

Undeclared name (no `new`) → free/public constant, adversary knows it
from the start. Fine for a plain public channel. Use `new` only when
the channel name itself must be unknown to the adversary at creation
(private/authentic channel).

## Freshness

`new` = globally unique, adversary-unknown at creation. Nonces,
session IDs, ephemeral keys are all just `new` values — same
guarantee, different role:

- Nonce — anti-replay
- Session ID — labels/distinguishes concurrent runs
- Ephemeral key — scopes key to one session (forward secrecy)

`~` marks fresh-sorted variables (`~n`, `~ltkA`, `~ek`) — use on any
variable bound to `new`.
